<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Minister Plays Down U.S. Drug Report </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Minister Plays Down U.S. Drug Report </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0504033094 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0206 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0504033094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] San Jose, 4 Apr (ACAN-EFE) -- Today, Costa Rican 
Security Minister Luis Fishman played down a U.S. State 
Department report that "money laundering" and drug trafficking 
and consumption are on the rise in Costa Rica. Fishman said the 
report admits that "there is virtually no corruption" in Costa 
Rica's police force, which is prevented from taking more 
effective action against drug trafficking because of a lack of 
financial resources. "I am proud because they say there is no 
corruption," the minister told ACAN-EFE, saying that contrary to 
what Washington says, Costa Rica has dealt "harsh blows" to drug 
traffickers in recent years despite the limited resources. 
Fishman said he "disagrees" with the assertion that Costa Rican 
policemen are unprofessional. He said that Puerto Limon on the 
Atlantic coast is a problem area and added that many resources 
have been allocated to fight drug trafficking and consumption. 
  The State Department's annual report, released today, 
highlighted the progress made by Central American governments, 
with the exception of Nicaragua and Costa Rica, in the fight 
against drug trafficking and money laundering. The report says 
the "laundering of drug money" is particularly serious in Costa 
Rica, Honduras, and Nicaragua, but virtually nonexistent in El 
Salvador. 
  The State Department praised Guatemala the most for its 
cooperation with Washington in several campaigns to eradicate 
cocaine and opium and to arrest drug traffickers. According to 
the State Department, meager resources and a lack of 
professionalism among security services preclude significant 
progress in the counternarcotics struggle in Costa Rica. The 
report says Puerto Limon has become the main point of contact 
between the Colombian island of San Andres, the Nicaraguan coast 
on the Caribbean, and the United States. At the same time, 
however, the report said there is virtually no corruption. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9897 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat065_f_94002" </HT>


