<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina Prefers Latin American Investment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Robaina Prefers Latin American Investment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0504022494 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0004 GMT 5 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0504022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Evening Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina began his 
official visit to Uruguay by meeting with President Luis Alberto 
Lacalle in Montevideo. Robaina's agenda in Uruguay includes 
meetings with Uruguayan Foreign Minister Sergio Abreu, political 
leaders, bankers, and businessmen. 
  In initial statements to the media in Montevideo, Foreign 
Minister Robaina said he told President Lacalle of Cuba's 
efforts to spur economic openness. The Cuban foreign minister 
reaffirmed that Cuba prefers investments from Latin American 
countries but welcomes investments from any country. According 
to Roberto Robaina, foreign investors find tourism, oil, nickel, 
citrus, and general agriculture the most attractive areas for 
investment. 
  Foreign Minister Robaina will conclude his official visit to 
Uruguay on 6 April, when he will travel to Argentina, Ecuador, 
Peru, and Paraguay. The visit to Paraguay is unofficial because 
Cuba does not have diplomatic relations with that country. 

</TEXT>

