<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. `Mobilization' Off East Coast Questioned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. `Mobilization' Off East Coast Questioned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0504160294 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1155 
GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0504160294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Once again, the waters of the Atlantic Ocean and the 
eastern coasts of the United States will be the stage for 
military manuevers by U.S. naval, air, and land forces. These 
manuevers are called the (Fleet-tex-2-94) Joint Exercise. 
Today's edition of the newspaper GRANMA points out that for the 
purpose of setting the inhabitants of all regions of the world 
at ease vis-a-vis the mobilization of its military forces, the 
U.S. Government usually announces that the maneuvers are routine 
or that they are merely innocent exercises. 
  In this case, GRANMA adds, the U.S. Department of Defense 
says its goal is to put its stamp of approval on a large portion 
of those forces to be mobilized to Europe. It is difficult to 
understand the essence of that idea when the allegedly innocent 
exercises include approximately 13,000 troops; 23 ships, 
including a nuclear-powered aircraft carrier; and more than 100 
airplanes. 
  GRANMA, which is the official newspaper of the Central 
Committee of the Communist Party of Cuba, also emphasizes the 
participation of an Argentine destroyer and submarine, which 
join a very dangerous military buildup in regions very far from 
their home base. Last, GRANMA underscores the moral, derived 
from another Creole saying: The road to hell is paved with good 
intentions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

