<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Brizola Rules Out Coalition With PT </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Brizola Rules Out Coalition With PT </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0504234694 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 5 
Apr 94 p A4 </F>

<F P=103> PY0504234694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Rio de Janeiro -- Former Governor Leonel Brizola 
(PDT) [Democratic Labor Party] has ruled out any possibility of 
an alliance with the PT [Workers Party] during the first or 
second round of the presidential elections. "An agreement with 
the current PT leadership is not viable," said Brizola, adding 
that he believes Luis Inacio Lula da Silva's candidacy is being 
artificially inflated by the surveys. "No one believes in the 39 
percent he is allegedly getting because that is what he obtained 
in the 1989 runoff election." 
  Regarding the possibility of an alliance with other parties, 
Brizola -- who yesterday lunched with Minas Gerais Governor 
Helio Garcia (PTB) [Brazilian Labor Party] at the Commercial 
Association of Rio de Janeiro -- said the only alliance already 
signed by the PDT is with the small National Mobilization Party 
(PMN). The former governor said a coalition with the PTB is a 
"natural" possibility. Regarding speculation that he would meet 
with PPR leaders, Brizola said: "Traditional politicians do not 
like me because they know I favor change and if I win the race I 
would end political chicanery." 
  Brizola resigned on 2 April to run in this year's elections. 
He said he was satisfied with what he did during his term, 
adding that no other governor did more. "They may have equaled 
me, at best," Brizola said. At the time the PDT governor left 
the government, he had the lowest popularity rate for any 
governor in the country. He was undecided whether to run for 
president or for the Senate. He said: "I am attracted to 
participate in the national campaign," adding: "This will be my 
last and greatest campaign. I will use all my accumulated 
experience." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

