<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deterioration in Relations With IDB, IRDB Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deterioration in Relations With IDB, IRDB Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0504123794 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 31 Mar 
94 p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PY0504123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maria Clara R.M. do Prado] </F>
  [Excerpt] Brazilian financial relations with the 
multilateral credit organizations -- the World Bank (IRDB) and 
the Inter-American Development Bank (IDB) -- have deteriorated 
in the last two years. In 1993, the country transferred a net of 
$1.744 billion to the two institutions, of which $1.467 billion 
was to the IRDB alone. 
  These transfers represent what the country had to pay in 
interest and servicing of the debt in exchange for what it 
received in disbursements by the two organizations. In the case 
of the IRDB, the situation is worse because its yearly 
disbursement to Brazil decreased from the already low level of 
$800 million at the end of the 1980's to about $500 million the 
IRDB has been disbursing annually since 1992. In 1993, the IRDB 
disbursed only $471 million to Brazil and received $1.318 
billion in debt service and $620 million in interest. 
  The value of the new loans also is decreasing. From the 
$1.344 billion the IRDB granted Brazil in 1992, the amount 
dropped almost 50 percent in 1993 and totaled only $636 million. 
As for the IDB, the loans decreased from $1.117 billion to $514 
million. 
  All sorts of problems help explain the deterioration of our 
relations with these organizations. Brazil has no resources to 
offer as compensation for these loans, the projects' management 
is ineffective, there is a lack of continuity in the projects' 
domestic administration, and there are bureaucratic difficulties 
that delay the flow of resources. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-9983 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat066_m_94014" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-066 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sanchez Parodi Accepted as New Cuban Ambassador </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sanchez Parodi Accepted as New Cuban Ambassador </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0504233994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2002 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY0504233994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia, 4 Apr (EFE) -- The Brazilian Foreign 
Ministry today reports that Brazil has agreed to the naming of 
Ramon Sanchez Parodi as new Cuban ambassador to Brasilia. 
Sanchez will replace Jorge Bolanos. 
  In an official note, the Brazilian Foreign Ministry stressed 
that between 1977 and 1989 Sanchez occupied "one of the most 
relevant and sensitive posts for Cuban diplomacy" as head of the 
Cuban Interests Section in the United States. 
  From 1989 to date, Sanchez, 55, has been a vice minister of 
foreign relations, a post to which Bolanos has now been 
promoted. Bolanos held the post of Cuban ambassador to Brazil 
for 7 years. 
  Brazil resumed diplomatic relations with Cuba in 1986 during 
Jose Sarney's government, after an interruption of more than two 
decades following the implementation of the one-party system on 
the island. 
  Brazilian companies have shown increased interest in 
economic 
and financial relations with Cuba, especially following the 
recent economic opening process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

