<F P=100> CARIBBEAN </F>
<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Robaina: Uruguay Willing To Negotiate Havana's Debt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Robaina: Uruguay Willing To Negotiate Havana's Debt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL0504161394 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1100 
GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0504161394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto Robaina has announced 
in Montevideo that Uruguay is willing to negotiate [a no 
congelar] Havana's debt with Uruguay and to seek a solution that 
is favorable for both countries. Robaina made these statements 
minutes after his meeting with Enrique Braga, director of 
Uruguay's central bank. 
  Robaina met earlier with Uruguayan President Luis Alberto 
Lacalle, with whom he exchanged ideas on, among other issues, 
the upcoming Ibero-American Summit scheduled to be held in 
Cartagena de Indias, Colombia; the changes being made in certain 
areas of the Cuban economy; and preparations for the conference 
entitled "The Nation and the Emigre Community" scheduled to be 
held in Havana this month. 
  Robaina's agenda included meetings with General Liber 
Seregni 
Mosquera, president of the Uruguayan Broad Front; a very 
interesting meeting with the foreign relations committee of the 
Uruguayan Parliament, where Robaina explained our country's true 
situation; and meetings with Uruguayan intellectuals and Cubans 
residing in Montevideo. 
  Robaina's agenda for today includes talks between foreign 
ministries, a meeting with his Uruguayan counterpart Sergio 
Abreu, and contacts with several Montevideo television networks 
and Uruguay's most important newspapers. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10004 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat066_c_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-066 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  5 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Salinas Appoints New Chief of Presidency Office </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Salinas Appoints New Chief of Presidency Office </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0504202094 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 1905 GMT 5 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0504202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mexico City, 5 Apr (NOTIMEX) -- It was reported 
today that Mexican President Carlos Salinas de Gortari 
designated Santiago Onate Laborde as chief of the Office of the 
Presidency of the republic. A communique from the Presidency 
states that Onate replaces Jose Cordoba Montoya, recently 
appointed Mexican representative to the Inter-American 
Development Bank. 
  Onate Laborde has been Mexico's permanent representative to 
the OAS (1991-92), federal attorney for protection of the 
environment (1992-93), and federal deputy (1985-88). Before his 
appointment, Onate was secretary of international affairs of the 
National Executive Committee of the ruling Institutional 
Revolutionary Party. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

