<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amorim: Ties With PRC `Strategic Partnership' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amorim: Ties With PRC `Strategic Partnership' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0704023794 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 6 
Apr 94 p 9 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0704023794 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Luiz Orlando Carneiro] </F>
  [Text] Brasilia -- At the end of his five-day visit to the 
PRC on 5 April, Foreign Minister Celso Amorim said Brazilian-PRC 
relations have reached the dimension of "strategic partnership." 
Amorim was received by President Jiang Zemin and vice premier 
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen, among several other 
high-ranking Chinese officials. He negotiated an agreement on 
principles about aerospace cooperation, which will be signed by 
President Itamar Franco in May during his official visit to 
Beijing. 
  One of Minister Amorim's most fruitful meetings was the one 
with Wang Zhongyu, minister in charge of the state Economic and 
Trade Commission. Zhongyu showed special interest in a joint 
venture [two preceding words in English] project at Carajas 
[Para State]. The project involves the construction of a 
deep-water port in the PRC with the capacity to receive large 
cargo (300,000 metric tons) vessels. Minister Wang also showed 
interest in Minister Amorim's request that special attention be 
given to Brazilian companies' desire to participate in PRC 
biddings in the areas of infrastructure and telephone systems. 
  Brazil and the PRC, which are celebrating the 20th 
anniversary of their diplomatic relations' resumption, are 
intensifying cooperation in the scientific and technological 
fields. Brazil proposed the reactivation of the bilateral 
agreement for cooperation in the nuclear field, which was signed 
in 1984, and reiterated the importance of the project for the 
construction of ground observation satellites (CBERS 
[China-Brazil Earth Resources Satellite] Program). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10013 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat067__a94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-93-067-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  1 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lula's PT Changes Strategy, Targets Cardoso </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Lula's PT Changes Strategy, Targets Cardoso </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0504005694 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 1 
Apr 94 Business and Finance Section p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0504005694 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese and Finance </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Workers Party (PT) has decided to change its 
campaign strategy in light of Progressive Renewal Party Paulo 
Maluf's decision not to run and of the launching of Fernando 
Henrique Cardoso Brazilian Social Democracy Party as the 
anti-Lula candidate. Coordinators of Luis Inacio Lula Da 
Silva's campaign believe that Cardoso, supported by the Liberal 
Front Party and by the Brazilian Labor Party, will be the elite 
groups' candidate and that, therefore, a polarization of the 
election is inevitable. The PT will intensify its attacks on 
the economic plan and on Cardoso as the main target of its 
criticism. 
  Until former Sao Paulo Governor Orestes Quercia is confirmed 
as the Brazilian Democratic Movement Party presidential 
candidate in May, the PT will not make any attacks on him. 
Lula's campaign coordinators believe Maluf's decision not to 
run could have stemmed from a behind-the-scenes accord with 
Quercia. PT campaign official Greenhalgh believes Maluf has 
backtracked because those who always supported him have endorsed 
Cardoso's candidacy. "All the partners of Paubrasil [which 
contributed to Maluf's campaign] have been consulted," he 
ironically said. Until now, the PT has harshly criticized 
Maluf. From now on, the PT tone will change and its criticism 
against Cardoso will intensify. 
  The PT no longer considers Cardoso the third alternative, 
having moved up to second place and become Lula's main 
adversary. Greenhalgh added: "Cardoso has time and again 
disappointed the people by telling them to forget what he said 
earlier and by deciding to run without worrying about the future 
of the plan." He was thus anticipating the PT line of attacks 
against Cardoso. Within this new strategy, the PT will insist on 
securing the support of Rio de Janeiro Governor Leonel Brizola, 
(Democratic Labor Party). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

