  [Text] Montevideo, 4 Apr (PL) -- Uruguayan President Luis 
Alberto Lacalle met today with Cuban Foreign Minister Roberto 
Robaina, who is on an official visit to this South American 
nation as part of a regional tour. 
  Robaina met with the Uruguayan president at his private 
residence, where the two men exchanged ideas on the upcoming 
Ibero-American Summit to be held in Cartagena, Colombia, as well 
as Cuba's economic changes. 
  During the meeting, the Cuban foreign minister explained to 
Lacalle about preparations for the conference "The Nation and 
Emigration," to be held in Havana from 22 to 24 April with the 
participation of 200 representatives of the nucleus of people 
who have emigrated from the island and settled in approximately 
20 nations. 
  The foreign minister also met with Enrique Braga, director 
of 
the Central Bank of Uruguay, to discuss the possible payment of 
the Cuban foreign debt, estimated at over $30 million. 
  Robaina indicated it was possible to find a favorable 
solution for both nations after he explained that Havana could 
supply Montevideo with specific items (medicines and medical 
equipment). He announced the upcoming visit of high-level Cuban 
banking officials to initiate negotiations. 
  Robaina also met with General Liber Seregni, president of 
the 
Coalition of the Broad Left Front, and legislators, who are 
members of the Uruguayan parliament's foreign relations 
commission. 
  According to the agenda, talks between the Cuban foreign 
minister and his colleague Sergio Abreu will begin tomorrow. 
  On Thursday, Robaina will continue his tour to Ecuador, 
Peru, 
and Argentina. He will conclude his trip with an unofficial 
visit to Paraguay, a nation with which Cuba does not have 
diplomatic relations. 

</TEXT>

