<H3> <TI>   Irish Delegation Continues Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Irish Delegation Continues Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0504040994 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1756 GMT 4 Apr 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA0504040994 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 4 Apr (PL) -- Today, Joe Jacob, vice 
president of Ireland's lower house, began the second day of his 
visit in which he is expressing his solidarity with Cuba and 
exploring the possibilities for broadening commercial and 
cooperation links. 
  Cuban parliament sources told PRENSA LATINA that Jacob is 
heading a delegation comprising five parliamentarians whose goal 
is to encourage good relations between the two countries and to 
continue broadening them. 
  The parliamentarians will meet with Jose Ramon Balaguer, 
member of the Council of State of the Communist Party of Cuba; 
Isabel Allende, vice minister of foreign relations; and Carlos 
Salsamendi, president of the Chamber of Commerce. 
  Official sources noted that the visitors expressed their 
desire to seek ways to strengthen relations between the 
legislative bodies of the two nations. 
  During their stay, which will continue until 10 April, the 
visitors are also interested in learning about the tobbaco 
industry as they explore areas in which Ireland and Cuba might 
broaden trade relations. 
  The Irish delegation will visit Pinar del Rio Province, 
Cuba's westernmost province, as well as public health, 
agricultural, and sports centers. Public health, agriculture, 
and sports are areas in which they will study prospects for 
broadening and diversifying cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

