<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commission to Investigate Plot </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission to Investigate Plot </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0604220394 Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA in Spanish 6 Apr 94 p 54 </F>
<F P=103> PA0604220394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Last night, the National Congress appointed the 
Constitutional Compliance Commission [Comision de Cumplimiento 
Constitucional] to monitor the investigation into the plot to 
assassinate President Carlos Roberto Reina and establish the 
motives behind it all. 
  Congress President Carlos Roberto Flores Facusse explained 
that he understands the concern of the opposition political 
parties. They are annoyed because Lucio Izaguirre, President 
Reina's private secretary, charged there were opposition plans 
to destabilize the government. "This democracy is costing the 
Honduran people dearly, particularly the political parties, 
without whom there would be no state of law," he said. "To 
generalize in such a way is improper and constitutes an attack 
on the country's institutional structure. This is why we are 
taking these charges seriously and instructing the 
Constitutional Compliance Commission to stay abreast of the 
trends this investigation may uncover," he said. 
  He said appropriate measures will be taken if, after 
examining the results of the investigation, he finds reason 
enough to believe that false accusations have been made that 
could violate the state of law or damage the dignity of the 
political parties. He also demanded the commission file a 
detailed report to the congressional plenum, explaining how well 
founded these charges are in order to reach the proper decisions. 
  The commission members are Jorge Roberto Maradiaga, Rodolfo 
Irias Navas, Jose Raul Pineda Alvarado, Oscar Armando Avila 
Banegas, Gautama Fonseca, Hector Ramon Trochez, and Luis German 
Lagos. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10063 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat067_h_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Legislators React to Assassination Plot </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Legislators React to Assassination Plot </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0604212994 Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA in Spanish 6 Apr 94 p 55 </F>
<F P=103> PA0604212994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tegucigalpa LA TRIBUNA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Members of the legislative branch reacted with 
rejection, condemnation, uncertainty, and doubt upon learning of 
the plot against President Carlos Roberto Reina. Although many 
refused to comment, others expressed surprised at the report 
because they had met with the president that morning and he did 
not say anything to them. Congressmen also referred to 
criticism by several Hondurans who are accusing the government 
of using the situation as a smokescreen to cover up the economic 
measures, noting that if that were the case, it would be very 
irresponsible. 
  Rafael Pineda Ponce, National Congress first vice president, 
called the act condemnable "because no one has the right to take 
the life of any citizen, much less the president." In his 
opinion, the state security organizations should conduct the 
investigation because their constitutional mission is to 
guarantee the Hondurans' lives and property. If the idea was to 
distract people to stop them from criticizing the rising fuel 
and milk prices, that would be really irresponsible because the 
country is ready to make a social pact among all political, 
social, and economic forces. "The country does not belong to 
the Reina administration or anyone in particular. It belongs to 
everyone, from the most arrogant and haughty to the humblest 
citizens," he added. 
  Liberal Alberto Orellana said he was surprised by the report 
and deplores the incident. "Whether we like it or not, Reina is 
the democratically elected president and we must condemn such a 
situation," he said. He did not rule out the possibility that 
the thwarted attack was a result of the people's desperation 
over spiraling costs and dire poverty. "We can think of so many 
things, things that someone starving might do, but hopefully it 
is nothing like that, only a false alarm," he added. 
  Roberto Micheletti, secretary general [of the Liberal Party 
Central Executive Council], said he was surprised by the report 
and termed the situation loathsome. "If it is confirmed, I hope 
the responsible parties will be turned over to the courts and 
sentenced to the full extent of the law because this country 
elected its leaders democratically and we want to live in 
peace," he stated. 
  When asked about accusations that the incident could be a 
smokescreen, he said "if that were the case, it is wrong and 
undignified. To show such disrespect for the president's life, 
to cover up a situation that we Hondurans are experiencing, is 
wrong and reproachable," he said. 
  Liberal wing head Santiago David Amador condemned any attack 
against the life of a human being, in this case the president of 
the Republic. He said he is waiting for a report from the Armed 
Forces and asked God "to enlighten the minds and attitudes that 
bring disgrace to the people." He stated he is satisfied with 
the intelligence service reports and ruled out the possibility 
that the report was made to hide the country's real situation. 
"No way, one thing cannot be compared to another. One is an 
economic issue, and the other is a human life," he said. 
  Nationalist Jorge Zelaya termed the report dubious because 
"it is strange military intelligence did not issue it, just as 
they did not issue the report when there was an attack against 
former President Roberto Suazo Cordova. Strangely enough, the 
report comes from the Government Ministry when it happens that 
economic decisions have been made and measures taken at the same 
time," he said. 
  Cesar Castellanos, chief of the nationalist wing, said there 
is some doubt because Honduran and Nicaraguan military 
authorities have been at odds over the reports they have given. 
"I would like to wait a little longer and learn about the 
investigations because I have found a series of contradictions 
and facts that are disconcerting. It has been 15 days and 
nobody has been arrested and there is no specific 
investigation," he noted. He added that the statements being 
made clearly show the military authorities were not properly 
informed and now they are trying to say that they knew about 
something when they really did not. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-10064 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat067_h_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-067 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  6 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Honduras </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alleged Plotter Claims Innocence </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Alleged Plotter Claims Innocence </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0604193294 Managua BARRICADA in Spanish 6 Apr 94 pp 1, 10 </F>
<F P=103> PA0604193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua BARRICADA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Marta Marina Gonzalez and Arquimedes Gonzalez] </F>
  [Text] Santiago Rivas Betancourt is 27 years old and 
allegedly one of the terrorists who were supposed to kill 
Honduran President Carlos Roberto Reina for $400,000. He told 
BARRICADA: "I have never had anything to do with such a plan. I 
went to Honduras to buy spare parts. We are clean. We did not 
plan any murder. I am incapable of becoming involved in such a 
plan," he has said, expressing his willingness to appear before 
police authorities to clarify the entire situation, because, he 
said "I am innocent." 
  Betancourt said he did in fact travel to Honduras with Luis 
Rene Quintero Gonzalez and Jose Arguello Hernandez at the 
beginning of March. They went to buy spare automotive parts. 
When they arrived in Honduras, he added, they were robbed at the 
San Miguel market in Comayaguela and "left penniless." They 
decided to go to the Nicaraguan Consulate. The ambassador gave 
them 100 lempiras so they could return to Nicaragua. He 
recalled they had requested a 90-day multiple entry permit. 
After the robbery, he said, "I had to ask an uncle, who lives in 
Honduras, for thirty lempiras to complete the return fare and 
then travel back to Nicaragua alone." 
  He admitted meeting Luis Rene Quintero Gonzalez, the alleged 
informant, by pure chance. He met Jose Arguello Hernandez, 
another alleged plotter, when they were cell mates serving time 
at Esteli Penitentiary. Santiago Rivas Betancourt said he was 
arrested last year for insulting a law officer. Unofficially it 
is reported, however, he served time for illegal possession of 
weapons and drugs. He also said he was a former member of the 
Sandinist People's Army, where he served as a battalion chief in 
the Army's 5th Infantry Company, in the country's first region. 
Betancourt lost his left hand in a mine explosion, just before 
being discharged. This happened in 1990, when he switched to 
civilian life. 
  Unofficial reports state Luis Rene Quintero Gonzalez, the 
alleged informant of the "plot," has an automotive body shop 
near Bello Horizonte Rotonda. None of the mechanics working in 
that area was able to give any information about Quintero. They 
did say, however, the police had been there at 1830 looking for 
the body shop and its alleged owner. A reliable government 
source has confirmed to BARRICADA the police were on Quintero 
Gonzalez' trail. They had not yet arrested him when we went to 
press. Unofficial reports state Quintero lived in the 
neighborhood of Fundeci, Managua. It was impossible to contact 
him there either. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

