<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   British Foreign Secretary Views Privatization </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    British Foreign Secretary Views Privatization </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY0704154494 Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 6 
Apr 94 Section 1 p 4 </F>

<F P=103> PY0704154494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Antonio Carlos Seidl] </F>
  [Text] British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd, 64, has said 
in Sao Paulo that British consulting firms and investment banks 
have "specific" and "practical" interest in "actively" engaging 
in the privatization of the Brazilian electricity sector. 
  Hurd yesterday began a four-day visit to Brazil to promote 
relations between the two countries. In Brasilia tomorrow, he 
will meet with President Itamar Franco, with Finance Minister 
Rubens Ricupero, and with Foreign Minister Celso Amorim. 
  At Bandeirantes Palace, in southern Sao Paulo, Hurd met with 
Governor Luiz Antonio Fleury Filho, with whom he addressed the 
plan for privatization the Sao Paulo potable water service. 
  Hurd added that Great Britain has successfully privatized 
the 
electric power and potable water sectors. 
  "As a result of this," he went on, "British enterprises have 
direct experience in privatization management, and a new class 
of entrepreneurs who specialize in denationalization." 
  Hurd said the British Government will consider reopening 
official export credits for Brazil, which were suspended four 
years ago when Brazil stopped amortizing its debt to the Paris 
Club. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

