<F P=100> Nicaragua </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputies on Drug Trafficking, Money Laundering </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputies on Drug Trafficking, Money Laundering </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0604194894 Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0604194894 </F>
<F P=104>  Managua Sistema Nacional de Television Network 
in Spanish 0200 GMT 6 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] With approval of the new narcotics law being debated 
by the National Assembly, Nicaragua will establish the legal 
framework for combating drug trafficking more efficiently, but 
the law alone is not sufficient, Deputy Carlos Gallo, chairman 
of the Human Rights Committee, has said. We need resources and 
assistance even from the U.S. State Department. 
  [Begin Gallo recording] The State Department can help in 
obtaining assistance for Nicaragua's police apparatus to combat 
it. You know how precarious the National Police budget is. [end 
recording] 
  The law is also being drafted to fight money laundering, 
which has not taken hold in Nicaragua. 
  [Begin Luis Humberto Guzman, Christian Democratic Union 
deputy and National Assembly president, recording, in progress] 
...the report does not review the volume of financial 
transactions in Nicaragua's banks. We could not necessarily 
talk of money laundering; at least not for now. [end recording] 
  Nicaragua has not reached the level of drug trafficking of 
other countries. 
  [Begin Guzman recording] Perhaps Nicaragua's only 
implication 
is that its territory and air space are used as a 
drug-trafficking and transshipment point. [end recording] 
  The law may be passed in the next four weeks. Controversial 
topics will be DEA operations in our country and the extradition 
of nationals, something our Constitution bars. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

