<H3> <TI>   Privatization To Resume Under New Council President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Privatization To Resume Under New Council President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0604134694 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 4 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0604134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Ecuadoran President Sixto Duran-Ballen has sworn in 
banker Marcel Laniado as new president of the National Council 
of Modernization, Conam. This institution will oversee the 
privatization process. It is expected that with this 
appointment Ecuador will embark on an aggressive state 
modernization process by reactivating the sale of state-run 
companies. This process lost steam in the past few months, as 
Conam has not had a president since mid-1993. 
  Laniado said that a common effort must be made to achieve 
our 
nation's social and economic well-being. Laniado noted it is 
impossible to develop unless all the community's sectors 
participate. He thus stressed: I invite you all to cooperate. 
  The government will submit the rules of the State 
Modernization Law approved in December 1993 by the Congress 
after an eight-month study. 
  Conam was created in 1992 at the conservative government's 
initiative. But is has been in serious crisis since the 
resignation of its board of directors last year. 
  [Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish at 2335 GMT on 4 April, in a 
Quito-datelined report on the same topic, adds: "Finance 
Minister Cesar Robalino announced that the first state-run 
company to be privatized will be the telecommunications company 
(Emetel), a public sector giant. Defense Minister Jose Gallardo 
gave the assurance that while companies operated by the Armed 
Forces are diverse, the military will agree to any required 
sales. Also in line to be privatized are important petroleum 
and energy companies considered strategic by previous 
governments."] 

</TEXT>

